Halley on OpenRC
================

OpenRC is a system-level service manager and has no per-user session
supervisor, so there is no user "halley" service to install here. A Wayland
compositor is a user-scoped session, not a system daemon — launch it the same
way you would on any init:

1. Seat management
   Install and enable `seatd` (or `elogind`) as a system service so the tty
   backend can acquire the seat via libseat:

       rc-update add seatd default
       rc-service seatd start

   Add your user to the `seat` group (or the group seatd is configured for).

2. Start the session
   Use a display manager that reads Wayland session entries — greetd is the
   common OpenRC choice, but SDDM and LightDM also work. They read:

       packaging/wayland-sessions/halley.desktop

   which runs `halley-session`, which in turn execs `halley --session`.

   For a login-shell / TTY autostart instead of a display manager, run
   `halley-session` (or `halley --session`) directly from your shell profile.

Halley detects that systemd is not the booted init at runtime (it checks for
/run/systemd/system) and automatically skips all systemctl integration, so no
extra configuration is required. To force the init-agnostic path explicitly
(e.g. if the systemd package is installed but not booted), set:

    export HALLEY_NO_INIT_INTEGRATION=1
